                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d42">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.G Commercial Agreement/56: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-26T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 26, 1934—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>273. Report of the Second Committee, in line with the Consulate’s 265, September
                    24, 11 a.m.,<note n="14" xml:id="d42fn14">Not printed.</note> was adopted by the
                    Assembly today. In the course of a speech the Argentine delegate called
                    favorable attention to the Pan American Agreement. There was no further
                    discussion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
